metadata.name: Kinetic Bug #103
metadata.description:
Best viewed on a decent GPU,  because physics simulations are performance intensive. Otherwise you might encounter a bug...

In a world of digital data, a new life is born. We are not alone...
Explore how kinetic bugs make their way through the world. What will their destiny be?
It's curious that we can sympathize to a predefined creature living it's predestined life in the digital world. Coding in the computer abyss reveals interesting worlds.

Keyboard
[ space ] - jump
[ click ] - increase velocity briefly
[ r ] - restart simulation
[ s ] - save image
[ f ] - full screen

Mobile
[ two finger tap ] - jump
[ tap ] - increase velocity briefly

metadata.name: Saccharine Biomes: Hills #14
metadata.description:
Saccharine Biomes is a series of generative projects by Empress Trash that explore glitchy abstract aesthetics in generative tokens with different environments, flora and fauna in pretty super colorful pallets. These are created with both hand drawn elements and glitch photo collage to generate digital mixed media piece unique to each hash. 

7 Attributes total

8 - Backgrounds
6 - Sky Variations*
5 - Shiny Variations*
6 - Middlegrounds
6 - Foregrounds
6 - Foiliage Variations*
8 - Animals

Each Attribute has weighted rarities for fun times!
*includes 1 variation of none. 

All collage elements are CC0 and all tokens generated from this release are CC0.

metadata.name: Citta #237
metadata.description:
Citta as mind Citta as city. 

Citta is city of interconnected minds from future of Metropolis IX(Project id:13292), after singularity people uploaded their consciousness into inorganic self-constructing structures. 

There are 13 different mind-hives named with upper case letters, only "MC-00001" is monochrome rest is in color. "SCMB" and "SCCB' are in spiral formation due to their nature.

Press 1 to 8 export PNG 1000px to 8000px 
9 exports 10000px PNG 

Exports are dependent on CPU, so larger export might take time. Please be patient. If you cannot export reach me out.

Works best in Chrome browser. 

Created with p5.js and canvas api.
Murat Atimtay 2022 | @atimtay | www.muratatimtay.com

metadata.name: Sand Shapes #83
metadata.description:
An experiment in line texture by Nate Donato, this piece features lines composed of a sand-like particle texture.  Bounds around line generation properties were set loosely, resulting in many possible line characters with unique weights, wobbles, and more.  Lines are generated in individual layered segments one by one, resulting in a pleasing animation of gradual composition as they compose one of twelve possible shapes, in one of eight possible color schemes.  

Each "line" is made up of thousands of points, and so rendering the live view of this piece may be computer intensive.  As an added bonus a small amount of proprietary line data is emitted to the development console, allowing the minted collection to serve as a palette of potential line qualities for the artist to use in future works.  Any owners of pieces used in this way by the artist on future projects will be granted a share of said future project's royalties.

In active live view, press [1] to view medium res, [2] to view high res, and [0] to return to original viewport width view.

Written in vanilla JavaScript without the use of external libraries.

metadata.name: A Clock #16
metadata.description:
This generative token is based on a project I originally coded in late 2014, possibly my first creative project in JavaScript during graduate school at NYU ITP, which has run here since then: https://rossgoodwin.com/clock

The text in this case is not generated, but rather (legally) snipped from public domain e-books on Project Gutenberg (https://gutenberg.org/), and recontextualized as a real-time clock.

The editions vary in color palette and font choice, each with unique text for every minute determined by the clock's unique hash. For nearly all word/phrase blocks in the template system, there exist 512 possible excerpts you could receive, and countless possible combinations thereof. Additionally, 16 possible color palettes, 8 possible fonts, and many bezel types will determine your clock's visual appearance.

Unlike my original 2014 iteration, I wrote this clock in Vanilla JS with zero dependencies. (Largely, that's thanks to eight additional years of programming experience.) As a result, it's faster (once loaded) and more responsive as well.
